value as a worthwhile return on investment. Specific, definable activities, such as research experience, first-year experience, and experiential learning, are marketed as delivering precise skill sets in the form of an individual educational package. Through ethnography-based analysis, the contributors to this volume explore how these commodified "experiences" have turned students into consumers and given them the illusion that they are in control of their investment. They further reveal how the pressure to plan every move with a constant eye on a demonstrable return has supplanted traditional approaches to classroom education and profoundly altered the student experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCollege students as consumers. 0aEducation, HigherxEconomic aspects. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspects. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aUniversities and collegesxSociological aspects. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aBaldrige, Anastassia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergbauer, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBodinger De Uriarte, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCai, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHandler, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobson, Shari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLadousa, Chaise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaviolette, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMajumdar, Usnish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPosecznick, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShumar, Wesley, econtributor.4ctb4https: